title: Support multiple dynamic inputs in custom ops
body:
**Description**: 
Support multiple dynamic typed inputs in custom ops. #6066 enabled support for dynamic typed inputs/outputs but there was a minor limitation in the implementation. For illustrative purposes, if there was a dynamic input 1 (returned `ONNX_TENSOR_ELEMENT_DATA_TYPE_UNDEFINED`  for the type) that was actually `int8` in a node and if there was another dynamic input 2 that is `uint8` in the same node, the current implementation would return an error while loading the model: `Type (T) bound to different types` because we were essentially binding only one type template parameter `T` for all the dynamic inputs. This change supports multiple type template parameters `T0`...`Tn` because they need not be inter-dependent at all.

Also, added a couple of important checks:
1) If an output was dynamic typed, there must be atleast one dynamic typed input from which we may be able to infer the type of the output at runtime. (This assertion was missing in the original implementation and it basically allowed a dynamic typed output without any dynamic typed inputs).

2) If there are more than 1 dynamic typed inputs, there cannot be any dynamic typed outputs as type inference is now impossible for the generic case. There may be multiple dynamic typed inputs as long as the types of the outputs are all fixed. (#6469 requests support for this exact case)  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolves https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6469
Good to include this enhancement for 1.7 given that this feature (dynamic inputs/outputs for custom ops) will ship in 1.7

title: Rebase ortmodule-api branch on master
body:
The point of this PR is to validate builds. Once that is done we will need to force push this branch on thiagofc/ortmodule-api to rewrite the history.

For the ease of reviewing, apart from rebasing I made the below changes to make builds pass on master (please note in the dev branch we DO NOT run all the CIs that run in master, hence there were bugs checked-in that broke the build):
	
 - Moved event_pool, message_queue and bias dropout fusion to core from training, since they are used in inference code where training headers are not accessible and CIs on master will fail at compilation stage.
 
 - Reduced binary size to make Minimal build CI pass, here I basically wrapped background thread related code in TRAINING ifdef since it was written in inference_session.cc which is a common file for inference and training.
 
 - A recent pytorch nightly build broke ORTModule because they got rid of container_abcs, I changed ORTModule to import it from collections.abc
 
 - Also validated ORTModule runs expected batch size with expected throughput on NV-BERT-Large.
 
 - History looks clean now!  Its easy to see what this feature contains and all the fluff from master is gone.

title: MLAS: add uint8_t NHWC max pooling
body:
**Description**: Add support to transform graphs containing uint8 MaxPool to a custom operator that supports NHWC format that can be more easily vectorized.

**Motivation and Context**
Add support to:
1. Extend the NCHW->NHWC graph transformer to recognized MaxPool(uint8) and replace this with com.ms.NhwcMaxPool(uint8).
2. Implement the com.ms.NhwcMaxPool operator.
3. Implement a MLAS routine to do a vectorized MaxPool using an indirection buffer.

Although the current implementation of NhwcMaxPool is single threaded, this easily beats the old code path of transposing back to NCHW, running a scalar MaxPool, then typically transposing back to NHWC for additional convolutions.

title: Do not review yet - ORTModule - FastGeluFusion fix
body:
**Description**: During the GPT2 model benchmark using ORTModule, found FastGeluFusion doesn't happen when fp16 is enabled. The reason is due to extra Cast nodes exported from PyTorch, which break the matching patterns.

The fix is to add extra pattern logic in the second formula to conver this case.
With the fix, the throughput for GPT2 is improved another ~8% comparing to the test without the fix.

body:
**Description:**
[FIX] Openvino EP build on windows.

**Motivation and Context:**
The issue is wchar_t is UTF-16 on windows while on other platforms
such as Linux and MacOS, wchar_t is UTF-32.

so wide Unicode string has to be converted to an UTF8 string
for sure on windows else the compiler will throw an error.

This commit fixes this issue.

title: Make it easier to fold MakeString usages to reduce binary size.
body:
**Description**: 
MakeString is often used with string literals, which have a type of char[n]. As the 'n' differs based on the length of the string literal it makes it harder to re-use the combinations of types in the MakeString template instantiation.

Add a layer to decay a char[n] argument to char* so that we can re-use the MakeString implementation for a combination of types more effectively.

Tested with various platforms and build types to validate. All tests showed a reduction in size. Example reductions for two main build types:

Android MinSizeRel minimal build, static libc++, no ops, no exceptions (i.e. ORT mobile base build)
 - Before: 1,129,344
 - After: 1,096,576
 - Saving: 32KB

Windows Release build with all ops
  - Before: 7,244,800
  - After: 7,193,088
 - Saving: 50KB


**Motivation and Context**
Reduce binary size from MakeString

(1) Restore original CUDA kernel as default, and add an environment variable to enable new CUDA kernel for experiment.
(2) Update convert_longformer_to_onnx: support  transformers 4.3.2, where an extra parameter is added to LongformerSelfAttention.forward; add an option --export_padding so that user could choose whether to have padding logic in ONNX model.

(2) There is additional constraint that number of global tokens <= attention_window.

title: Copy forward signature from PyTorch model.
body:
The original PyTorch `forward` method has some defined input parameters, for example, parameters a, b, c: `def forward(self, a, b, c)`.
But ORTModule's `forward` method defined as `def forward(self, *inputs, **kwargs)`.

The user code may inspect the `forward` signature.
Specifically, Hugginface's data loader uses the signature to decide which data is actually needed.

One aspects of the issue, is that different ORTModule instances can exist at the same time and have different `forward` signatures.

This PR solves the described problem by dynamically creating `_forward` function, binding that dynamically created function to the ORTModule's  `forward`  method, and copying the signature of the original model's `forward` using `functools.update_wrapper`.

title: Support nested sequence and mapping types in ORTModule
body:
**Description**: Support for nested sequences and mappings as output types as defined by users in ORTModule.

Changes in this pull request will enable users to return more complex types in the forward method of their ```torch.nn.Module``` such as nested dictionaries and nested sequences.

The solution can be summarized with these points:
- The ```ORTModule``` saves a new attribute called ```_flattened_output_module``` which is another ```torch.nn.Module``` called ```FlattenedOutputModule``` which is responsible for transforming the output of the original module (which can be a complex structure) to a flat tuple structure.
- Since, the exporter understands the flat tuple structure, exporting this ```_flattened_output_module``` to an onnx model does not lead to any errors.
- Before returning the output to the user, the output (from the backend) needs to be unflattened back to the original structure (that the user is expecting).
  - To address this, a schema of the output is saved called ```_original_module_output_schema```.
  - This schema represents the original output where all ```torch.Tensor```s are replaced with a ```_TensorStrub``` object so as to avoid holding on to memory that was needed by the ```torch.Tensor```.
  - This schema is used to unflatten the output from the backend (which is obtained as a flattened tuple) into the output structure that is expected by the user by replacing all ```_TensorStub```s with the values from the output tuple.

This pull request adds a new file ```_ortmodule_output_transformation.py``` that is responsible for all the output parsing and transformations. In addition to the above work, a few unit tests are also added that validate the support for complex return types.

title: Move create kernels earlier during session init
body:
This change split the kernel initialization logic into two part, the constructor and a virtual function SecondaryInit(). The goal here is to move the create kernel phase earlier, at least before const tensor de-serialization, and for some kernel init logic that depend on weight tensor values, those are moved to SecondaryInit()

**Motivation and Context**
*Problem*:

Some kernels prepack some const input tensors (weights) into another buffer, maintained internally in the kernel. After prepacking, the const tensor should be deleted, with its memory buffer reclaimed. 

Unfortunately, this leads to large amount of wasted memory in most cases, as these buffers are allocated either on memory pattern, or on memory arena, which makes deallocation impossible.

*Solution*:

We need to make the memory pattern planner aware of the prepacking, so that it won't trace const tensors that are going to be prepacked and deleted. Unfortunately this can not be done in a jiffy, as only the kernel object would know whether a weight tensor should be prepacked or not. But the memory pattern planner is run before the kernel objects are created.

So this change is the first step of implementing the solution: we move the kernel creation earlier, before memory pattern planner  runs. In the future we will have other changes for rest of the work.

title: Fix app packaging in UWP
body:
**Description**: Workaround for #6249

**Motivation and Context**
Nuget supports multi-plarform/multi-architecture packages and Nuget/msbuild picks the correct DLLs from `runtimes\` if you follow their naming conventions ([available here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/create-packages/supporting-multiple-target-frameworks#architecture-specific-folders)). But at some point it started copying files from `native` into UAP builds, causing #6249. I'm not sure if this is a bug in msbuild or our understanding of "native" is incorrect (maybe "native" means supported everywhere, and we should use another moniker for non-UWP? [The reference of existing monikers is here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/reference/target-frameworks#supported-frameworks)).

Anyways, `csharp/src/Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning/Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning.targets` already handles the logic to choose which DLLs to copy so we should do fine if Nuget doesn't interfere. This PR stops Nuget from messing with our packaging. There isn't a straightforward way to tell Nuget to stop doing it (see [discussion](https://github.com/NuGet/Home/issues/329) and [discussion](https://github.com/NuGet/Home/issues/452) - [the](https://github.com/NuGet/Home/issues/5986#issuecomment-732401471) [supported](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/consume-packages/package-references-in-project-files#controlling-dependency-assets) [way](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/reference/nuspec#specifying-files-to-include-in-the-package) is adding some tags to PackageReference, which means the **consumers** of the Nuget package would have to add a couple of lines to their project), so my proposed workaround is simply renaming the native folder so Nuget doesn't attempt to copy DLLs automatically.

Not following the folder naming convention and doing the copying through msbuild targets is also done in other projects (e.g. see [Microsoft's WebView2](https://github.com/MicrosoftEdge/WebView2Feedback/issues/461#issuecomment-731551769) and I don't expect it to cause issues.

---

I tested my changes by locally editing a Nuget package and they fix UWP. I seem to have recently lost permission to queue jobs at aiinfra, so I couldn't do a clean run of the YAML job to see if it's actually producing a valid package. Before merging we should run the Nuget packaging pipeline and test if both UWP and Desktop are fine. I'll be out of office for the next few days, so @smk2007 will likely be the one driving this PR.

title: Liqun/ort module perf1
body:
**Description**: Log performance date.
Currently performance logging is done within onnxruntime/orttraining/orttraining/models/runner/training_runner.cc. To adapt to OrtModule, naturally the logging shall be done at the frontend. It allows us to log same performance data for training with both Pytorch and ORT so we can make direct apple-to-apple comparison. 
To log performance data at the frontend also eases code maintenance.
This is the phase 1 of performance logging work which simply make powerbi database connection and inserting performance data into the database. In the next phase we will finalize Bert and Huggingface training scripts and to put logging code into the training script.

**Motivation and Context**
- To replace manual perf run before devops pipeline
